04268nam a22005535i 9780822381709DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19911991ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223817097 a10.1515/97808223817092doi  a(DE-B1597)554247  a(OCoLC)1136309438  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN843b.S24 1991 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a809/.89732201 aSaldívar, José David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Dialectics of Our America :bGenealogy, Cultural Critique, and Literary History /cJosé David Saldívar; Stanley Fish, Fredric Jameson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1991] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tI. Metahistory and Dependency -- t1. The Dialectics of Our America -- t2. "Squeezed by the Banana Company": Dependency and Ideology in Macondo -- t3. Chicano Border Narratives as Cultural Critique -- tII. Magical Narratives -- t4. The Real and the Marvelous in Charleston, South Carolina: Ntozake Shange's Sassafrass, Cypress & Indigo -- t5. The Hybridity of Culture in Arturo Islas's The Rain God -- tIII. Caliban and Resistance Cultures -- t6. The School of Caliban -- tAfterword: Postcolonial Borders, Dissent, and the Politics of the Possible -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJoining the current debates in American literary history, José David Saldívar offers a challenging new perspective on what constitutes not only the canon in American literature, but also the notion of America itself. His aim is the articulation of a fresh, transgeographical conception of American culture, one more responsive to the geographical ties and political crosscurrents of the hemisphere than to narrow national ideologies.Saldívar pursues this goal through an array of oppositional critical and creative practices. He analyzes a range of North American writers of color (Rolando Hinojosa, Gloria Anzaldúa, Arturo Islas, Ntozake Shange, and others) and Latin American authors (José Martí, Roberto Fernández Retamar, Gabriel García Márquez, and others), whose work forms a radical critique of the dominant culture, its politics, and its restrictive modes of expression. By doing so, Saldívar opens the traditional American canon to a dialog with other voices, not just the voices of national minorities, but those of regional cultures different from the prevalent anglocentric model.The Dialectics of Our America, in its project to expand the "canon" and define a pan-American literary tradition, will make a critical difference in ongoing attempts to reconceptualize American literary history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822381709zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822381709423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822381709.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles